FAQs
What are the benefits of studying in the USA?

Studying in the USA offers numerous benefits, including access to world-class education, a diverse and multicultural environment, and excellent career opportunities. The USA is known for its innovative teaching methods and strong emphasis on research.

How can I apply to a US university?

You can apply to a US university through platforms like the Common Application or individual university portals. Start by researching universities and courses, then prepare the required documents, including academic transcripts, personal statements, letters of recommendation, and standardized test scores (like the SAT or ACT). Ensure you meet all deadlines and follow the application guidelines provided by each university.

What scholarships are available for international students?

The USA offers various scholarships for international students, including merit-based and need-based scholarships. Many universities have their own scholarship programs, and there are also external scholarships offered by organizations such as EducationUSA and government agencies.

Can I work while studying in the USA?

Yes, international students on an F-1 visa can work up to 20 hours per week during term time and full-time during holidays, but only on-campus jobs. After completing the first academic year, students may apply for Optional Practical Training (OPT) to work off-campus in their field of study. Working while studying can provide valuable experience and help supplement your income, but it's important to balance work and academics.
